</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[809,1426,199,1079]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">
<emphasis box="[809,946,199,220]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Description:</emphasis>
This genus was originally created for the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1924" box="[896,1056,229,251]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Eptesicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="zuluensis">
<emphasis box="[896,1056,229,251]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Neo. zuluensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on it having ‘the cranium slightly raised above the level of the muzzle’ (
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts A" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" pagination="245 - 263" refId="ref23406" refString="Roberts A. 1926. Some new S. African mammals and some changes in nomenclature. Annals of the Transvaal Museum 11: 245 - 263." type="journal article" year="1926">Roberts, 1926</bibRefCitation>
). The close relationship between this taxon and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Thomas, 1901)" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[809,1138,321,343]" genus="Neo." pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" rank="species" species="somalica">
<emphasis box="[809,962,321,343]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Neo.somalica</emphasis>
(Thomas, 1901)
</taxonomicName>
has long been recognized, and the two are sister taxa in our phylogeny.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[809,1426,199,1079]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">
Based on our genetic and morphometric analyses presented above, we have expanded this genus further to include the following species: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Bocage, 1889)" baseAuthorityName="Bocage" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Vesperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guineensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Neo. guineensis</emphasis>
(Bocage, 1889)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Seabra, 1900)" authorityName="Keyserling &amp; Blasius" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Seabra" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Vesperugo" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anchietae">
<emphasis box="[1139,1314,475,496]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Neo. anchietae</emphasis>
(Seabra, 1900)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Goodman et al., 2015)" baseAuthorityName="Goodman" baseAuthorityYear="2015" box="[944,1420,505,527]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Hypsugo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bemainty">
<emphasis box="[944,1121,505,527]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Neo. bemainty</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Goodman SM &amp; Rakotondramanana CF &amp; Ramasindrazana B &amp; Kearney T &amp; Monadjem A &amp; Schoeman MC &amp; Taylor PJ &amp; Naughton K &amp; Appleton B" box="[1141,1408,505,527]" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" pagination="988 - 1018" refId="ref21583" refString="Goodman SM, Rakotondramanana CF, Ramasindrazana B, Kearney T, Monadjem A, Schoeman MC, Taylor PJ, Naughton K, Appleton B. 2015. An integrative approach to characterize Malagasy bats of the subfamily Vespertilioninae Gray, 1821, with the description of a new species of Hypsugo. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 173: 988 - 1018." type="journal article" year="2015">
Goodman 
<emphasis box="[1268,1324,505,527]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. These are all small-sized pipistrelle-like bats with a distinct bacular morphology (
<figureCitation box="[1265,1353,566,589]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="13.[144,226,1119,1141]" captionTargetBox="[147,766,197,1073]" captionTargetId="figure-544@13.[145,766,195,1079]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 5. Bacula of the four clades within formerly or traditionally recognized as Neoromicia: A, Laephotis kirinyaga (FMNH 234639); B, Neoromicia somalica (FMNH 215614); C, Pseudoromicia kityoi (FMNH 223211); and D, Afronycteris nana (DM 13013). Note the three-pronged tip in Neoromicia, the straight shaft with spatulate tip at an angle of 45° in Laephotis, the long, curved shaft with bilobed tip in Pseudoromicia and the deeply bilobed base and gently curved shaft in Afronycteris. Scale bars: 1 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). The baculum (~1.5–2.0 mm in length) is shorter than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monadjem &amp; Demos &amp; Dalton &amp; Webala &amp; Musila &amp; Kerbis Peterhans &amp; Patterson" authorityYear="2021" box="[843,1023,628,649]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pseudoromicia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[843,1023,628,649]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Pseudoromicia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and similar in length to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1901" box="[809,927,659,680]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Laephotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[809,927,659,680]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Laephotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monadjem &amp; Demos &amp; Dalton &amp; Webala &amp; Musila &amp; Kerbis Peterhans &amp; Patterson" authorityYear="2021" box="[990,1137,659,680]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Afronycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[990,1137,659,680]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Afronycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It has a characteristic shape, with a thick base that is weakly bilobed, a shaft with a straight outer margin and slightly curved inner margin, and a unique three-pronged (cross-shaped) tip that is set at a slight angle to the shaft (
<figureCitation box="[936,1023,812,834]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="13.[144,226,1119,1141]" captionTargetBox="[147,766,197,1073]" captionTargetId="figure-544@13.[145,766,195,1079]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 5. Bacula of the four clades within formerly or traditionally recognized as Neoromicia: A, Laephotis kirinyaga (FMNH 234639); B, Neoromicia somalica (FMNH 215614); C, Pseudoromicia kityoi (FMNH 223211); and D, Afronycteris nana (DM 13013). Note the three-pronged tip in Neoromicia, the straight shaft with spatulate tip at an angle of 45° in Laephotis, the long, curved shaft with bilobed tip in Pseudoromicia and the deeply bilobed base and gently curved shaft in Afronycteris. Scale bars: 1 mm." pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). They also have a more inflated braincase than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1901" box="[1009,1131,842,863]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Laephotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1131,842,863]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Laephotis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but not as inflated as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monadjem &amp; Demos &amp; Dalton &amp; Webala &amp; Musila &amp; Kerbis Peterhans &amp; Patterson" authorityYear="2021" box="[809,955,873,894]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Afronycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[809,955,873,894]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Afronycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which they differ in many other respects (for more details, see the description in the account of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monadjem &amp; Demos &amp; Dalton &amp; Webala &amp; Musila &amp; Kerbis Peterhans &amp; Patterson" authorityYear="2021" box="[932,1073,935,956]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Afronycteris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[932,1073,935,956]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Afronycteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). They lack the white wings of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Monadjem &amp; Demos &amp; Dalton &amp; Webala &amp; Musila &amp; Kerbis Peterhans &amp; Patterson" authorityYear="2021" box="[809,985,965,986]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Pseudoromicia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[809,985,965,986]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Pseudoromicia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and have bicoloured fur on both the upper and under parts. All five species are essentially savanna or woodland species, with four occurring in southern and eastern Africa and 
<collectingCountry box="[1197,1341,1057,1079]" name="Madagascar" pageId="13" pageNumber="1127">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
